He said, you know, my daddy brought them in here, and he was afraid that this was too severe a weather that they wouldn't be able to live in this country in the wintertime, that it would be too cold.
And he said, you know, we had the shed.
I said, yes, I remember that very well.
And I said, you remember that we hitched them to the wagon, a little old cart that your daddy had

made for us and he told us whatever we did not to run down that hill not to go down that hill because they wouldn't be able to hold it back he didn't have any harness that would hold a wagon back but you know we got in it and rode in this wagon down the hill and we turned over at the bottom you remember that he said yes and i said you remember i was skinned up
And I didn't have a bit of hide left on my nose.
He said, yes, I remember that.
And I know that what happened to me, I got a spanking.
And I said, well, I didn't get a spanking, but I never will forget Grandma Chapman putting camphor on it.
And he just set me afire, and I screamed bloody murder.
And she was trying to get the Dobie Grint out of, it just grazed my nose.
It had Dobie Grint all in it.
She's trying to get that out and clean me up, and I just thought I was ruined.
And he said, that's so right.
I said, do you have a picture of those goats?
And he said, yes, I do.
I said, I'd be happy if you'd send a picture of that to me.
And there it is right up there.
That's great.
First Angora goats, registered Angora goats, has ever brought in to Blanco County.
That's grand.
Right there.
And then, by the same token, he said, well, he said, you know how we used to sweat those pecans out?
I said, yes, but you tell people today that you sweat pecans, and they just don't know what you're talking about.
But what...

they did they would thrash the pecans even though the hulls on them were still green and not yet dry enough to peel off and they would put them in a big box and let them go through a sweat and then they would turn dark and you could peel them that's right and old timers did that and he was asking me and I said yeah but now then they let them go and he said
Well, you know, the squirrels got so many of them.
I said, yes, the squirrels and the crows and the coons all ate on them until then.
And that's the reason that old timers took them out early and took them off and let them go through a sweat and they put them in these boxes.
And he said, well, another thing that has puzzled me, and I know that it happened, but I'm not able to
put it all together.
I said, well, what was that, Lou?
And he said, what about the peach kernels that we, or peach seeds and the plum seeds we had?
I said, well, we put them out and we washed them off and got all of the hide and everything, all the meat off of them and dried them and took them to town.
and sold them.
And we sold peach seeds.
He said, do you know for what they were used for?

I said, well, some were used for when they planted to re-bud and to re-graft, and some were used in medicines, and some were used in face cosmetics, and I said there were different uses of the peach kernel and the plum kernel.
I really don't really remember, but I know that
that we would always sell our peach seed.
And he said, yeah, that wasn't the only thing we sold either, was it?
And I said, to make money.
I said, no, it sure wasn't.
I said, we'd pick up every medicine bottle it was and wash it and sold medicine bottles to the drugstore for extra cash money.
And pick up a beer bottle and sell you two.
Now that's how we made our extra spending money.
Selling bottles, peach seeds.
Of course we sold our pecans.
And every Saturday we'd take our butter, eggs, cream to town.
That was extreme.
Who would you sell it?
Fredericksburg or Johnson City?
Right here.
In Johnson City.
Right here in this little town.
They'd take it off.
The stores would buy it?
The stores would buy it.
And I don't know how in the world we didn't have any ice.
How did they keep that cream?
Now you tell me.
I don't know.
We didn't have any ice here.
We brought our ice in here.
by truckloads and big blocks of ice.
But I don't remember those stores having ice to put on cream.
But I'm sure they did because they couldn't keep it otherwise.
Did they bring it up from Austin?
Yeah, they brought it up from Austin on flatbed trucks.
I'm sure, yeah.
I know they did.
Yeah, that they must have had.
But that was in later years.
But when we first started out, I know grandmother brought hers in buckets.
Where'd you store eggs?
Besides the cool houses.
Well houses.
Well houses.
You had well houses to keep that.
And I know, you know where the beauty shop is today?
Yeah, right.
There's a well behind there.
Yeah.
And there used to be a little house back of that that they kept all their eggs in.
Mm-hmm.
and all of the products back there in this little... That was the Witherson Spalding store.
And it's right where the National Park Library is today.
That was the Witherson Spalding store.
And they, on the east side, on the west side rather, they had hitching posts where they were all lined up there and they would tie their

their horses and their things there and that little alley between and it's still there today between Withers and Spalding store and the bank well they would have part of that cut off and that was all cemented and had that rock wall against it and they would put their put extra eggs out there and extra poultry and things in that little alley
To keep it cool.
Keep it cool.
Sure.
Well, let me ask you another question.
I know I've talked to you about the, what about the, you know, we were talking about the peddlers.
They used to come up here?
Yeah.
That's sort of trading.
What?
Tell us some more about that, because recently we met somebody whose great-grand, great-uncle was a peddler out of San Antonio.
Well, they came, they used to come up this way.
Yeah, they would always come through here, and they had certain, certain

of time to come maybe it would be on mondays or and fridays and they would come through here but they didn't come every week it'd probably be every two weeks they would come and they would take anything that you had to sell it would be butter eggs chickens turkeys uh
anything, vegetables, marketing goods, anything you had to sell, and they would trade it to you.
Well, we had no place to buy shoes.
We had no place to buy little dresses for children or little coats.
And I'll never forget the first pair of little shoes that I can remember that I cherished with all my heart was a little pair of,
patent leather shoes with red tops.
And they were laced up.
And Margaret got a pair.
I got a pair of black ones with red tops.
And Margaret got a pair of black ones with white tops.
And we thought they were the cutest things that ever was.
And they were.
And my mother traded them some chickens and some butter and some eggs.

to buy these shoes and what we called a bear skin coat and it was imitation fur mine was a red and Margaret's was a brown and they were really pretty little coats and they had a little head thing that we called well it was a it had a

pom-pom on the top of it and it came up to a point in the top and it was really a pretty cute outfit and the collar buttoned up close around the neck where you didn't have any cold air to get through and the head had a little cord that you pull down here that fit tight around your neck and you pull it around your head and put it down and you look like just like a little
Pekingese thing with that pointed tail up and the pom-pom on the top of it.
But it was real cute.
And it just matched my shoes and my little cap and thing.
And I well remember her paying for it with chickens and butter and eggs.
And then another thing that I remember quite so well, they brought a little stove

by and they sold also stoles for the farm people to buy and it was the cutest thing that ever was and he'd show how the how you could push the the how compact it was that the smoke would go up this way and out the out the regular uh stove pipe rather than coming out all around the sides how well it was
put together and it was called Home Comfort Stove.
And they sold between four and five hundred dollars.
Now that was many, many moons ago.
That was when I was just a little girl.
About how old?
Well, let me see.
We moved down here in 12.
And I would have been, that was when I was about six years old.
And they sold at that price then, and you said, well, you were so young, how do you remember that?
Well, I was taught from the word gold, the value of a dollar by my mother, and how much it meant, and how many it took to do this, and how many.
I knew.
And when he said it would cost that much, I knew that we
that that was impossible for us to buy.
And I never will forget telling the man, I said, well, we don't have that kind of money.
And he said, he looked at me and he said, well, how do you know?
And I looked up at my mother and I said, mother, do we have that?
She said, no, darling, we sure don't.
And he couldn't understand why I would know that we didn't have that kind of money.
Well, my mother taught me from the time I was old enough to talk that we didn't have too much.
And we didn't buy anything with what we could pay for.

Johnson, he, what did he do?

You know, we're not ready for that.
Manipulator.

Again, I'm coming from ignorance, based on what I knew, reading newspapers about him as president and so forth.
But if one of Miller's purposes was to picture him as a Mr.
Politician, and I'll step on anybody to get my point across and to

can persuade anybody then it does the job because again I don't know what was accurate or inaccurate about his childhood because that's well anyway I tell you that was the main thing and uh we were poor there was no question about it but of course his sister says we were not that we had as much as anybody we may have had as much but by golly is that a blessing or not
I was old enough to know.
And let me tell you, when you get up in the morning and you don't have anything to eat but cornbread and cream gravy, you know the times are hard.
And we lived on the ranch.
And it was hard times.
Our cattle were not fat enough to be slaughtered.
The deer were not fat enough to eat.

back in the 20s back in the 80s 30s listen it was rough going and we'd kill cottontail rabbits and that would be our meat every once in a while we'd find a fat coon and he never forgot that no and let me tell you
They can say what they want to.
But that was the thing that stuck in Lyndon Johnson's craw was the hardships that we went through as children and for eating and for cooking.
Listen, we had to pay for our education.
We had to buy our own books.
We didn't have free books when we went to school.
We bought our books.
And they were not the books that were
the latest off of the press, they were the ones that you could get the most of for that particular class.
And they may have been back in 1895.
I've got a scholar that was 1895 that I had in the fifth grade.
I've got arithmetic that was put out with Sutton and Bruce that I loaned to the library.
That was copyrighted in 1890.
And those are the books that you grew up using?
That was the books that I grew up using.
The Blueback Scholar and Sutton Bruce's Arithmetic.
And I went to school to a Mrs. Bruce that was a sister to the man that was author of this Arithmetic in Southwest Norman.
That's how old she was.
Ms. Bruce.
How about that?
So your education was what they could pull together.
And so Melissa was his.
And we paid for our education.
We only had a seven-month school year.
And two months of it was paid tuition.
I can only remember one time going to school with paid tuition.
My mother was a teacher and my daddy was a teacher.
And I stayed at home those two months and studied.
And then when preschool opened for five months, I went to school for five months and made a grade in five months.
The thing is, we've sort of systemized everything that we lose touch with the fact that people in the community life still take one career and stick with it for the rest of their lives.
You don't have to be a jack-of-all-trades in your education.
Again, who's teaching and who's not this year, right?
I look back
Of course, I know that Kitty Pie and I were talking the other night.
See, I'm four years older than she is.
And she said, you know, when I think about it, we have been a wonderful family.
I said, we sure have.
And we have seen the change.
and the times that have gone and come.
And I said, no other generation has had as many changes as you and I have seen.
I said, how many times have we ridden on a freight wagon from here to Austin, pulling bales of cotton to the market to be shipped to Galveston?
That's where our market was, Galveston.
You heard that old saying, sleep in the wagon yard?
We slept in the wagon yard.
Leonard East Wagon Yard, down the old first street.
Golly.
Here, I've met every astronaut that has ever been up.
Right here at this little town.
From the man on the moon to the wagon train to Austin.
Maybe you change.
Well, you know, the people who have come out of your generation, Ava, and people who have come up in mine since World War II, I mean, we don't know.
I mean, I'm lucky.
My family was your generation.
Yeah.
And since I was an afterthought, an accident down the line, so I see a bridge with your generation.
The majority of people that are my age are not.
No.
Then they're children are not.
No.
Yeah.
And it's quite a loss of that identity that America changed right here in your generation.
Harvey was telling me, he says, mother, he said, I want to tell you something.
Well, I told you about riding a racehorse.
for Roy Stubbs.
And he took this horse and sold it for $500 for a polo pony.
He said, I was in San Antonio a couple weeks ago to see the doctor and he said, Mother, I want to take you out and show you Roy Stubbs' polo patch that he still has, still operating.
He's 90.
92 years old.
Still operating it in San Antonio.
And he said, I said, well, don't.
I said, that is okay.
And so Roy told Corky about me riding his horse and me getting sent to Smith, old Atlanta.
And that Atlanta polo team was number one in Texas.
And here I am, a country girl, standing on the sideline watching the races.
And Roy Stubbs walks up to my daddy and says, I don't have a rider for my horse and I need one.
He said, I've got a rider for you right here.
My daddy said that.
And he said, who?
He said, Little Ava.
And I stand there looking over the fence at these horses getting old.
I just heard him say Little Ava, and I turned around.
And he said, go get your boots on.
I said, but I'm free.
My boots is in the wagon, not with a hat.
And I went and got my boots.
And he said, do you have any spurs?
I said, no, I didn't bring any spurs.
Roy said, I got a pair.
Well, you know what pole spurs are.
They just have a knob on them.
They don't have any gears.
Just a knob.
And I said, has this horse ever been ridden with pole spurs?
Roy said, no.
I said, well, she may throw a nuclear over that fence.
He said, oh, no, I don't think so.
I said, well, we better try before I get out there on that track.
You know, with the poles first.
And so we turned around two or three times, and Karen and I did it with the poles first.
And she just put a figure eight in that tail and just whirled it.
And I knew if I didn't turn many times, she'd throw me the tail over the fence.
I knew that, you know, when I'd see that tail with me.
Roy, I got on, and I rode her out.
And just about the time I got better than a little halfway, I heard my daddy holler out, put the bug to her sister.
And I knew what that meant.
It meant to whip her up.
And old Roy said, give her the reins, give her the reins.
Well, I knew if I gave her the reins and then hit her,
that I'd never stop when I got to the end.
I didn't think I would, that we'd just keep going.
But I did just what they told me, because they seemed to be knowing.
Well, we didn't stop at the gate.
We just hurtled that gate just as pretty as it pleased and just kept circling.
But I grabbed the reins, I'll guarantee you.
But we didn't even stop at the skater.
I'll never forget that.
But to think the polo pins are still operating the same thing.
And it always still takes horses down it.
That's something else.
For life, for you.

Nothing.

The state tradition.

She's

My land, I can remember when I'd sit on an old disc plow driving four mules all day long and plowing in the field.
I didn't think there was anything wrong in it.
I was helping my daddy make a living.
I'd get on a cultivator.
I could set a cultivator.

You have to set those
those little plows to where they just go exactly by that, by the stalk of cotton or this corn.

And let's see, home canning, carrying meat, and marketing.
Yeah.
No sense pertaining to culture?
Absolutely nothing.
That's where I lived and what I did.
Right, it was a necessity for me to know this.
It was a necessity.
And it was short course.
And you know, if a woman went down there in the 30s and 40s to take that, that burn, they were just almost ostracized.
Now, I'm not kidding you one.
That's right.
And they looked at you.
But these were special courses that I even offered for extension services.
For extension services, and I went and took them.
I think one of them cost me $90.
I know it wasn't an awful expensive thing because we didn't have it.
But what I did, I paid for it.
In a summer's time, the old food jar company hired me to put on demonstrations to use their jars to canvass and I paid for it.
Where did you do these demonstrations?
Right down here at the hardware store.
And at the different club meetings throughout the county.
Sort of like the Tupperware lady.
You just go from community to community and you go to someone's house and you put on these demonstrations, sell the jars.
Oh, honey, I've done everything from Cape Cod to Hickory Den that was honest and honest to make a living, to get by.
Milk cows, milk 24-headed cows day and morning and night.
We sell milk in this town.
She didn't have any.
But as I say, you're not alone.
There are other people here, like yourself, who have to do the same thing.

And you pick yourself up with the bootstraps and say, it's a better way.
I can do that.
But you didn't decide to teach until late in life, really.
No, I didn't.
Now, how long until you decided to go back to college?
Well...
I'll tell you, I went back in 48, in the summer of 48, and took my first 12 hours of school.
And I stood that summer for an emergency certificate.
And I got it for six years.
If you made an average of 85, you could get it for six years.
So I had 18 subjects that I took.
And I got it for six years.
I came back up here and I started teaching.
I taught in the fall of 48.
And in 50, I walked down the aisle.
With my diploma from Trinity University, my BS degree.
You have to go on school nights, right?
And going every night, teaching all day and going every night to school.
Then, and that was in 50.
Then I said, well, I'm through.
And my husband said, oh, no, you're not.
I said, the heck, I'm not.
I'm tired and I'm going to quit.
He said, no, you're not.
You're going after that master's.
I said, oh, well, I don't care whether I ever get a master's.
No, you're going to.
So in 1951, I started after my master's degree in January.
In 1952, I had my master's degree.
Taught school every day.
Never attended a...
I attended summer, one summer, in college.
And you went back to Southwest Texas for that?
Mm-hmm.
But you always made contributions to make to Southwest Texas.
Huh?
You made contributions as a student.
Oh, yeah.
I know.
You brought as much into your work as...

I guess I did.
I've heard.

I enjoyed that.
I enjoyed it a lot.

Uh-huh.

but there were not some big black community here no there's not any there aren't any black there's no black neighborhood there's no members around here this is a totally black absolutely county or no no no after the civil war and this is something else blanco county is the only county in the south that followed through exactly as the rules asked that every uh
male and female, 21 years of age, given a plow, Georgia stock plow, a mule, and 20 acres of land.
They did that, and they put them over in the county, in the south end of the county.
They bought the land, and these Negroes would have to preempted that land before it was given to them.
And then after they had lived on it a number of years after, they could have it as theirs.
But no white person could ever buy a foot of that land.
So long as any of its lenient descendants lived, it was theirs.
And it is still there.
It is still there.
And they can't get a clear title to anything that they've got over there.
Now, we've had a couple come in here from the north and bought up some land, but they don't have a title to it.
No way can they get a title to it.
And these neighbors kept the names.
of their masters that mourned them.
